^["intent"]{
 ~#goal: "Refactor the 2.5k-line stylesheet into responsibility-owned CSS layers while preserving GitHub Pages simplicity and preparing opt-in progressive enhancement plus seasonal ornament layers."
 ~#taste: "calm core, summoned delight, explicit containment, and seasonal wonder that cannot break the site"
}

^["development"]{
 lane: #craft_refactor
 ladder: #static_to_enhanced
 develops: [#css_layers, #progressive_enhancement, #seasonal_ornaments, #github_pages_assets]
 review_surfaces: [@plan, @artifact, @css, @semantics]
}

^["concept_index"]{
 primary: [#css_layer, #import_entrypoint, #enhancement_layer, #ornament_layer, #seasonal_token]
 tensions: [#visual_parity, #cache_graph, #ornament_debt, #motion_safety, #cascade_order]
 surfaces: [#home, #software, #spw_operator_atlas, #pretext, #play, #offline]
}

^["stream"]{
 >>[2026-04-09 23:40] observe - `public/css/style.css` is 2576 lines and mixes tokens, base shell, Spw components, Pretext lab, operator atlas, navigator, console, responsive rules, and spirit sequence styling.
 >>[2026-04-09 23:40] decide - Keep `/public/css/style.css` as the linked GitHub Pages entrypoint and split behind it first, rather than changing every HTML page or adding a build pipeline.
 >>[2026-04-09 23:40] decide - Treat seasonal features as progressive ornaments: opt-in, cacheable, reduced-motion safe, and unable to own core layout or navigation.
 >>[2026-04-09 23:40] taste - The refactor should make future SVG/Pretext/operator CSS easier to place without increasing visible noise. Ornament layers should feel like a removable glaze, not a second design system.
 >>[2026-04-09] style - The first seasonal proof is a character test, not a feature test. If the ornament could belong to any minimalist site's seasonal palette, it has not yet earned this one. The site's own grammar — operator geometry, brace topology, sigil forms, spirit arc sequences — is the source to draw from first.
 >>[2026-04-09] observe - Token names are style decisions. `--ornament-spring-accent` is a calendar entry. `--ornament-boon-field` or `--ornament-threshold-glow` arrive from the site's metaphysical vocabulary and carry different authoring residue — they connect the ornament to an already-live semantic web rather than importing a disconnected seasonal idiom.
 >>[2026-04-09] style - Personal ornament style should emerge under constraint: what does a motif look like when it can only use named tokens, respects reduced motion, and limits itself to a small surface footprint? That constraint is a creative filter as much as a safety rule.
}

^["open"]{
 ?[cascade_layers]: "Should the first split use native CSS @layer immediately or defer @layer until import parity is verified?"
 ?[season_loading]: "Should seasonal CSS be imported by style.css, linked per page, or lazy-loaded after core CSS?"
 ?[cache_policy]: "Should every seasonal file be precached, or should only the current season be cached?"
 ?[snapshot_baseline]: "What screenshot set is enough to prove the no-behavior CSS split?"
 ?[motif_vocabulary]: "What visual grammar should the first ornament come from — operator geometry, brace topology, spirit arc sequence, or a form the site implies but hasn't yet named?"
 ?[token_naming]: "Should seasonal token names derive from calendar seasons or from the site's own metaphysical vocabulary — charge, boon, bane, phase, threshold, discharge?"
 ?[signature_test]: "What makes a seasonal ornament feel native to this site — what would a reader who knows the operator atlas recognize as the same sensibility?"
 ?[personal_emergence]: "At what commit should the first ornament's motif source be logged as a deliberate taste decision rather than left as an implementation detail?"
}

^["commits"]{
 ~[1]: "#[css] - capture CSS split and progressive ornament plan"
 ~[2]: "&[css] - split style.css into stable layered imports without visual changes"
 ~[3]: ".[semantics] - formalize progressive enhancement and ornament safety contracts"
 ~[4]: "&[ornaments] - add opt-in seasonal ornament host and one quiet seasonal proof"
 ~[5]: "![css] - verify visual parity, reduced motion, offline cache, and mobile containment"
}

